      "question": "Should the marginals cache live inside the inference module (e.g. CurrentModelQueryBackend in current_model.py) or in the server adapter layer (server.py where refresh_market_compile_snapshot already lives)? The task description says 'inference module' but the invalidation trigger points (ProbabilityEdit, resolution) are wired in server.py.",
      "category": "design",
      "why_it_matters": "This determines the module boundary for the cache. Putting it in the inference module keeps the server thin but requires the module to accept invalidation signals. Putting it in the server keeps invalidation co-located with triggers but couples cache logic to the HTTP layer."
    },
    {
      "id": "q2",
      "question": "What exactly should be cached? Currently every query_market_marginals_for_inference call recompiles from scratch via compile_market_for_inference. Should we cache (a) the CompileResult/artifact per market, (b) the MarginalQueryResult per (market, context) pair, or (c) both?",
      "category": "requirements",
      "why_it_matters": "Caching only compile artifacts avoids redundant compilation but still requires query execution. Caching query results adds a second cache layer with its own invalidation semantics. The scope of 'junction-tree marginals cache' in the task title is ambiguous."
    },
    {
      "id": "q3",
      "question": "Should cache invalidation be hash-based (compare source_state_hash on query, serve cached if match) or event-based (explicitly invalidate/clear cache entries when mutations occur)? The codebase already computes canonical_json_hash for source state.",
      "category": "design",
      "why_it_matters": "Hash-based is simpler and naturally correct (stale data impossible) but requires hashing on every query. Event-based is faster at query time but requires every mutation path to remember to invalidate, which is a correctness risk."
    },
    {
      "id": "q4",
      "question": "The task says 'invalidated for affected variables.' In the current model each market has one variable, but conditional_marginals introduce cross-market context variables (e.g. market A's conditionals reference market B's variable). When market B's marginals change, should market A's cached conditionals also be invalidated?",
      "category": "requirements",
      "why_it_matters": "Cross-market invalidation is significantly more complex than per-market invalidation. It requires tracking a dependency graph of which markets' caches depend on which other markets' state. Getting this wrong means stale conditional probabilities."
    },
    {
      "id": "q5",
      "question": "Should EventTrade trigger cache invalidation? The T553 freeze document explicitly states 'EventTrade does not mutate market marginals in this stub' and does not trigger refresh_market_compile_snapshot. But the task description says 'when trades occur.' Is the task expecting us to add EventTrade as an invalidation trigger, or just document that it doesn't need one?",
